Reason no. 1087 that I love @Kinstretch / @FRC is that it helped solidify my understanding of what productive physical training actually feels like, in process, which is to say: it feels more like a series of questions, and less like a to-do list. Here are a few of my go-to's:
âWhat is my range of motion at my __(insert joint)___?
âWhat does ___(insert position)___ feel like?
âï¸How effectively can I create tension and torque at ___(insert joint/position/movement)___?
//
\\
//
Due to the huge (potential) range-of-motion available at the shoulder joint, "use it or lose it" is never more true than when we're talking about shoulder mobility.  By utilizing an FRC approach--systematically making each joint/position more functional--you find that a little bit of focused effort at YOUR crappy positions goes a long way when you then go use the shoulder in otherâany otherâcontexts. You just need the patience to ask the questions.
//
\\
//
Here I'm chipping away at Shoulder (GH) External Rotation. That's one of the shapes your shoulder NEEDs in order to pullup, press, handstand, not-feel-like-garbage, etc. //
\\
//
First, I'm showing Isometric contractions (PAILs/RAILs) to help solidify position (sped up 6x), then playing with KB Bent Press/Windmill/OH Squat to train into that range (not the first time I'm doing these--don't just do stuff you see on the internet unless you're clear about having the pre-requisites ð) and finally an unweighted version to focus on the regressive (short-angle) side of the joint (last clip is sped up to 4x). //
